In the context of mining reporting entities, 'new information or data' that could materially affect previous disclosures of Exploration Results or estimates of Mineral Resources or Ore Reserves refers to any subsequent information or data that may impact the accuracy or relevance of the earlier disclosure. This may include, but is not limited to:

* Any changes to material assumptions and technical parameters underpinning the estimates in the earlier disclosure(s) (Rule 11.12.1(2));
* Any new data that may affect the exploration results, mineral resources, or ore reserves estimates (Rule 11.12.1(2));
* Any updates or revisions to the earlier disclosure(s) that may impact the validity or reliability of the information presented (Rule 11.12.1(2));
* Any new information that may be detrimental to the accuracy or completeness of the earlier disclosure(s) (Rule 11.12.1(2)).

In order to ensure compliance with the regulatory requirements, Mining Reporting Entities must:

* Confirm in subsequent disclosures that they are not aware of any new information or data that materially affects the information included in the earlier disclosure(s) (Rule 11.12.1(2));
* Verify that all material assumptions and technical parameters underpinning the estimates in the earlier disclosure(s) continue to apply and have not materially changed (Rule 11.12.1(2));
* Ensure that any subsequent disclosure references the earlier disclosure that was in compliance with Rule 11.12.1 (Rule 11.12.1(1));
* Implement appropriate controls and procedures to identify, assess, and mitigate any potential risks associated with new information or data (COBS Rule 17.7.4).

By following these requirements and procedures, Mining Reporting Entities can ensure that they are providing accurate, reliable, and up-to-date information to stakeholders, and that they are comply with the regulatory obligations set forth in the relevant rules and regulations.

