The Financial Services Regulatory Authority (FSRA) recommends and requires specific policy features and insurance providers for Authorized Persons providing custody for Spot Commodities. According to the FSRA, a suitable insurance provider for custody purposes should hold an FSP for providing custody and have arrangements in place with MTFs or OTFs, if applicable. Additionally, the FSRA requires the Authorised Person to consider the following risks in its Internal Risk Assessment Process (IRAP):

a. Credit Risk, including Large Exposures and concentration risks;
b. Market Risk;
c. Liquidity Risk;
d. for Islamic Financial Business involving PSIAs, displaced commercial risk;
e. interest rate risk in the Non Trading Book;
f. Operational Risk;
g. internal controls and systems; and
h. reputational risk.

Moreover, the FSRA requires Authorized Persons to have margin requirements for Retail Clients, which vary depending on the type of product and customer. For instance, the FSRA requires a Retail Client to have posted margin of at least 3.33% of the value of the exposure for major currency pairs and relevant sovereign debt, 5% for non-major currency pairs, gold, and major equity indices, and 10% for commodities, excluding gold, and non-major equity indices, and so on.

Furthermore, the FSRA requires Authorized Persons to maintain capital requirements, which take into account the size, scope, complexity, and nature of their activities and operations. The FSRA may apply proportionality and consider higher regulatory capital requirements for high-risk Authorised Persons.

In addition, the FSRA requires Authorized Persons to maintain an Annual Report on Compliance, which includes a statement on the adoption of best practice standards, a description of any actions taken to achieve compliance, and a statement by Directors on the effectiveness of the Corporate Governance framework in promoting compliance.

Finally, the FSRA requires prior consent for Confidential Information sought by a party other than a governmental or regulatory authority, consistent with its general duty of confidentiality.

