In the context of Virtual Assets, the specific aspects of the AML Rules that are most pertinent for Authorised Persons to ensure compliance with anti-money laundering and countering the financing of terrorism are:

As highlighted in the REGULATORY REQUIREMENTS FOR AUTHORISED PERSONS ENGAGED IN REGULATED ACTIVITIES IN RELATION TO VIRTUAL ASSETS, the key requirements for Authorised Persons are to:

* comply with the UAE AML/CFT Federal Laws, including the UAE Cabinet Resolution No. (10) of 2019 Concerning the Executive Regulation of the Federal Law No. 20 of 2018 concerning Anti-Money Laundering and Combating Terrorism Financing;
* comply with the UAE Cabinet Resolution 20 of 2019 concerning the procedures of dealing with those listed under the UN sanctions list and UAE/local terrorist lists issued by the Cabinet;
* adopt international best practices (including the FATF Recommendations);
* consider climate-related financial risks that may impact their capital and liquidity positions over relevant time horizons (e.g., through their impact on traditional risk categories), as per Principle 6 – Incorporation of climate-related financial risks into capital and liquidity adequacy processes.

Furthermore, Authorised Persons should ensure that they have a comprehensive application of the AML/CFT framework in place, including full compliance with the AML Rules, and that they are reliable and independent, allowing them to comply with all applicable Rules of the Regulator.

In addition, when undertaking an assurance assessment of an eKYC System for the purpose of Rule ‎9.3.1A, a Relevant Person should seek to establish that the eKYC System is reliable and independent, and allows the Relevant Person to comply with all applicable Rules of the Regulator.

The above requirements are critical for Authorised Persons to ensure compliance with anti-money laundering and countering the financing of terrorism, and to maintain a reliable and independent eKYC System.

